00:03:37,280 --> 00:03:38,021
One is nostalgia.

65
00:03:38,021 --> 00:03:39,962
That's one of the biggest ones.

66
00:03:39,962 --> 00:03:41,303
It's about passion.

67
00:03:41,303 --> 00:03:43,084
It's about a longing for a time where

68
00:03:43,084 --> 00:03:44,745
we remember playing the games that we loved

69
00:03:44,745 --> 00:03:46,226
and how great that made us feel.

70
00:03:46,226 --> 00:03:48,067
It's about the challenge presented

71
00:03:48,067 --> 00:03:49,528
by a lot of older games.

72
00:03:49,528 --> 00:03:51,549
You can find games that are still challenging

73
00:03:51,549 --> 00:03:53,951
that are made today, but it's not as common

74
00:03:53,951 --> 00:03:56,252
since gaming has a broader fan base now.

75
00:03:56,879 --> 00:04:02,203
And it's about wild cards, which is sort of the more human element and wacky things that

76
00:04:02,203 --> 00:04:06,928
we as human being developers wind up putting in our games that in march of time and the

77
00:04:06,928 --> 00:04:10,151
polishing of development has kind of erased a lot of.

78
00:04:11,121 --> 00:04:12,062
First, let's talk about nostalgia.

79
00:04:12,062 --> 00:04:16,346
These are images that are very nostalgic for me,

80
00:04:16,346 --> 00:04:18,908
because I grew up in the 80s and early 90s

81
00:04:18,908 --> 00:04:22,652
playing role-playing games like the original Bard's Tale.

82
00:04:22,652 --> 00:04:24,573
I played all the Gold Box games from SSI.

83
00:04:24,573 --> 00:04:27,616
Those were the AD&D games set in the Forgotten Realms

84
00:04:27,616 --> 00:04:29,498
and the Dragonlance settings, which were a lot of fun.

85
00:04:29,498 --> 00:04:32,501
And also Darklands, which is a game that almost no one has

86
00:04:32,501 --> 00:04:33,762
ever heard of.

87
00:04:33,762 --> 00:04:35,904
But it's a very cool historical role-playing game

88
00:04:35,904 --> 00:04:37,445
set in the Holy Roman Empire.

89
00:04:37,705 --> 00:04:38,846
and it's a lot of fun.

90
00:04:38,846 --> 00:04:42,047
And whenever I see pictures like this, it draws me back to that time,

91
00:04:42,047 --> 00:04:43,868
makes me very excited and passionate.

92
00:04:43,868 --> 00:04:46,609
I forget all the bad things about those games.

93
00:04:46,609 --> 00:04:48,050
I just remember all the good things,

94
00:04:48,050 --> 00:04:50,131
and I wish someone would make more games like that.

95
00:04:50,131 --> 00:04:53,493
And that's the way people feel when they see a lot of the Infinity Engine games,

96
00:04:53,493 --> 00:04:55,353
is that feeling of nostalgia,

97
00:04:55,353 --> 00:04:58,015
remembering how fun it was and how much they loved those games.

98
00:04:59,422 --> 00:05:01,423
And the second part is challenge.

99
00:05:01,423 --> 00:05:04,005
Like I said, you can still find games being made today

100
00:05:04,005 --> 00:05:07,407
that are really emphasizing a very strong difficulty curve,

101
00:05:07,407 --> 00:05:09,209
things like Dark Souls, games like that,

102
00:05:09,209 --> 00:05:13,172
especially since we have a lot more smaller developers making

103
00:05:13,172 --> 00:05:15,373
more focused games for niche audiences.

104
00:05:15,373 --> 00:05:17,234
You can find very challenging games out there.

105
00:05:17,615 --> 00:05:21,577
But role-playing games have also broadened their appeal and their fan base,

106
00:05:21,577 --> 00:05:25,260
and you see a lot of games that are targeted for a very low level of difficulty,

107
00:05:25,260 --> 00:05:26,381
a very shallow learning curve.

108
00:05:26,381 --> 00:05:30,663
And when people think back to games like Baldur's Gate or Icewind Dale,

109
00:05:30,663 --> 00:05:35,607
they think of very, very challenging fights that might have taken them hours

110
00:05:35,607 --> 00:05:37,928
and a lot of cursing and reloading to get through.

111
00:05:39,247 --> 00:05:41,667
The last thing are wild cards and this is sort of what I said

112
00:05:41,667 --> 00:05:45,088
about human beings develop these games and when we were younger

113
00:05:45,088 --> 00:05:47,308
we put things in these games that when we look back at we

114
00:05:47,308 --> 00:05:51,629
kind of cringe. They're rough edges and goofy things, things

115
00:05:51,629 --> 00:05:53,770
like Noober. I don't know if you guys remember Noober from

116
00:05:53,770 --> 00:05:56,310
Baldur's Gate. He was an NPC that would approach you and he

117
00:05:56,310 --> 00:05:58,891
would not stop talking to you and it was sort of like coaxing

118
00:05:58,891 --> 00:06:02,832
you to kill him. Very, very obnoxious character but people

119
00:06:02,832 --> 00:06:05,653
still have fond memories of this guy because he's just a wild and

120
00:06:05,653 --> 00:06:09,193
wacky dude and then things like the golden pantaloons.

121
00:06:09,273 --> 00:06:12,137
goofy clothing item that you can find in Baldur's Gate.

122
00:06:12,137 --> 00:06:15,982
So, the modern development process in a lot of cases,

123
00:06:15,982 --> 00:06:17,804
especially with large development teams,

124
00:06:17,804 --> 00:06:20,268
it kind of files over the edges of these human elements

125
00:06:20,268 --> 00:06:22,370
that people, they actually find very endearing

126
00:06:22,370 --> 00:06:25,775
because they show that people have fun making games.

127
00:06:25,775 --> 00:06:28,118
That's one of the reasons why we started making games.

128
00:06:29,915 --> 00:06:33,218
So let's talk about the, some of the dangers of making a retro

129
00:06:33,218 --> 00:06:36,301
revival game. You can hit the wrong targets. You can just

130
00:06:36,301 --> 00:06:38,523
focus on the wrong things. You look at all the things that go

131
00:06:38,523 --> 00:06:40,825
into a game and you spend your time working on the things that

132
00:06:40,825 --> 00:06:42,447
no one gives a shit about.

133
00:06:43,017 --> 00:06:43,537
That's bad.

134
00:06:43,537 --> 00:06:46,658
You can design for a very tiny niche.

135
00:06:46,658 --> 00:06:49,519
We sort of admit that we are designing for a niche audience.

136
00:06:49,519 --> 00:06:51,339
We're not designing for everybody, clearly.

137
00:06:51,339 --> 00:06:53,240
We're not even designing for most gamers.

138
00:06:53,240 --> 00:06:55,940
We're designing for a smaller subset of people.

139
00:06:55,940 --> 00:06:57,661
But within that niche, there are even

140
00:06:57,661 --> 00:06:59,741
tinier and tinier niches of people

141
00:06:59,741 --> 00:07:03,402
that are more interested in very, very narrow elements.

142
00:07:03,402 --> 00:07:06,463
If you over-design toward one tiny niche,

143
00:07:06,463 --> 00:07:09,123
you will never broaden your appeal at all,

144
00:07:09,123 --> 00:07:11,104
which can also be bad because you presumably

145
00:07:11,104 --> 00:07:12,864
want to continue making games.

146
00:07:13,704 --> 00:07:15,105
You can also update too much.

147
00:07:15,105 --> 00:07:19,226
You can look at everything and say, you know what, let's fix and update all of this stuff.

148
00:07:19,226 --> 00:07:20,987
Some of that stuff you don't need to touch at all.

149
00:07:20,987 --> 00:07:22,267
You can just leave it alone.

150
00:07:22,267 --> 00:07:23,108
It's totally fine.

151
00:07:23,108 --> 00:07:27,169
So you can be careful and just say, you know what, leave that alone.

152
00:07:27,169 --> 00:07:31,571
Let's focus on things that really need to be improved and not, you know, not change

153
00:07:31,571 --> 00:07:32,111
everything.

154
00:07:32,579 --> 00:07:38,621
And the last part is missing the soul. This is a very ephemeral, feels-based thing, but it's very important.

155
00:07:38,621 --> 00:07:45,583
It's possibly the most important thing, because again, the reason why you get a lot of people interested in these sort of retro-revival games in the first place

156
00:07:45,583 --> 00:07:48,484
is because they're very passionate about the game itself.

157
00:07:49,227 --> 00:07:51,871
And if it doesn't really have the feeling of those games,

158
00:07:51,871 --> 00:07:54,955
if it doesn't evoke the sort of nostalgia

159
00:07:54,955 --> 00:07:56,757
that you're looking for, you fail.

160
00:07:56,757 --> 00:07:59,540
You can even make a good game that

161
00:07:59,540 --> 00:08:01,683
is sort of good to some people, but you're

162
00:08:01,683 --> 00:08:03,886
sort of making it for an audience in the first place.

163
00:08:03,886 --> 00:08:06,229
And if you miss that, then you've missed the point.

164
00:08:08,150 --> 00:08:12,974
Soul is elusive. So let's talk about soul, which is this very ephemeral thing.

165
00:08:12,974 --> 00:08:17,077
When people remember the things that they love, their memory can be selective,

166
00:08:17,077 --> 00:08:19,139
they can gloss over a lot of things,

167
00:08:19,139 --> 00:08:22,582
and most of what they remember is their emotional attachment to it,

168
00:08:22,582 --> 00:08:24,363
and little things that stick out to them.

169
00:08:25,043 --> 00:08:28,426
The individual elements that go into it contribute to the whole picture.

170
00:08:28,426 --> 00:08:31,809
So when you modify things, you have to be very careful about what you're modifying.

171
00:08:31,809 --> 00:08:35,953
You could tweak one tiny thing that turns out to be a very key component of what made

172
00:08:35,953 --> 00:08:37,835
that something very cool.

173
00:08:37,835 --> 00:08:42,459
And ultimately, the spirit of something is more important than actually getting it technically

174
00:08:42,459 --> 00:08:42,719
accurate.

175
00:08:42,779 --> 00:08:45,780
And in many cases, it's healthier if you're trying to modernize a game.

176
00:08:45,780 --> 00:08:50,643
The example, I'm wearing my Ducati shirt today, I'm glad I packed it, because I'm going to

177
00:08:50,643 --> 00:08:53,604
talk about how Ducati, a motorcycle manufacturer, updated.

