00:08:53,604 --> 00:09:01,187
The bike on the left is Mike Halewood's Isle of Man TT bike from 1978, and the bike on

179
00:09:01,187 --> 00:09:03,688
the right is a mid-2000s Sport Classic 1000.

180
00:09:03,688 --> 00:09:06,430
They look fairly similar.

181
00:09:06,690 --> 00:09:10,753
but they're not actually all that similar, but they capture the soul of the old bike. And

182
00:09:10,753 --> 00:09:15,618
that's why that bike immediately sold out and why I can never find one for a good price and I'm

183
00:09:15,618 --> 00:09:20,282
going to be mad for the rest of my life about it. But it goes to show that the spirit of the

184
00:09:20,282 --> 00:09:24,906
thing is what's important. It's less important than the exact specific details. So let's

185
00:09:24,906 --> 00:09:30,771
talk about some of the things we did in Pillars of Eternity and what went right and what went

186
00:09:30,771 --> 00:09:31,492
very not right.

187
00:09:32,508 --> 00:09:37,810
We decided from the beginning that we were going to be making 2D environments from an isometric rendered perspective.

188
00:09:37,810 --> 00:09:41,332
That was a core component of all the Infinity Engine games.

189
00:09:41,332 --> 00:09:43,432
We knew we were going to raise the resolution a lot,

190
00:09:43,432 --> 00:09:47,053
but we were still going to hand touch most of our environments because we did a lot of...

191
00:09:47,053 --> 00:09:51,155
After an environment would be rendered, we'd have 2D artists go back and touch them up.

192
00:09:51,155 --> 00:09:55,776
And that we were also going to try to add in a 3D lighting element, which was challenging.

193
00:09:56,590 --> 00:10:00,672
And I covered that in a little talk I did a few years ago.

194
00:10:00,672 --> 00:10:03,014
But basically, we managed to get 3D lighting

195
00:10:03,014 --> 00:10:06,155
into a 2D environment, and it was great.

196
00:10:06,155 --> 00:10:07,256
And a lot of the art that we looked

197
00:10:07,256 --> 00:10:10,717
at in terms of our inspiration was from the second edition

198
00:10:10,717 --> 00:10:11,118
AD&D era.

199
00:10:11,118 --> 00:10:15,160
So that, for me, is artists like Larry Elmore, Jeff Easley,

200
00:10:15,160 --> 00:10:18,581
Keith Parkinson, Clyde Caldwell, Fred Fields, and Gerald Brom,

201
00:10:18,581 --> 00:10:19,602
also just known as Brom.

202
00:10:19,602 --> 00:10:24,544
Overall, those artists used less saturated palettes

203
00:10:24,544 --> 00:10:26,385
than a lot of contemporary fantasy artists.

204
00:10:26,961 --> 00:10:29,786
and relatively realistic weapons and armor.

205
00:10:29,786 --> 00:10:32,451
So they look, you know, they're not, they don't really look historical,

206
00:10:32,451 --> 00:10:35,516
but they're a little more on the subdued side, especially when compared

207
00:10:35,516 --> 00:10:37,119
to a lot of contemporary fantasy art.

208
00:10:38,089 --> 00:10:42,632
Here are a few key images that we looked at when we were looking at our style.

