00:48:22,008 --> 00:48:26,610
the economy for where gold went. One of those was a durability

932
00:48:26,610 --> 00:48:27,050
system.

933
00:48:27,907 --> 00:48:30,010
Ooh, people didn't like that.

934
00:48:30,010 --> 00:48:33,573
That was something that Tim Cain and I worked on and proposed

935
00:48:33,573 --> 00:48:34,154
pretty early on.

936
00:48:34,154 --> 00:48:36,116
And we had a backer update about it.

937
00:48:36,116 --> 00:48:37,758
And there were, I mean, I won't say everyone.

938
00:48:37,758 --> 00:48:39,460
But there was a significant number

939
00:48:39,460 --> 00:48:42,103
of people that were like, this doesn't feel D&D-ish.

940
00:48:42,103 --> 00:48:44,205
This doesn't feel like it belongs in an Infinity Engine

941
00:48:44,205 --> 00:48:44,906
game.

942
00:48:45,506 --> 00:48:50,511
One thing that came out of that conversation is that a lot of folks on our forum said,

943
00:48:50,511 --> 00:48:54,175
you know, I don't really care that much if I wind up with a ton of gold toward the end

944
00:48:54,175 --> 00:48:54,575
of the game.

945
00:48:54,575 --> 00:48:58,359
That being said, I think we could have done a better job balancing the economy.

946
00:48:58,359 --> 00:49:02,643
I think some of the higher level crafting recipes, like if you want to upgrade a weapon

947
00:49:02,643 --> 00:49:03,844
to the really high tiers...

948
00:49:04,124 --> 00:49:08,807
We could have had those cost a huge amount of copper, which would have been a big improvement.

949
00:49:08,807 --> 00:49:13,349
And the stronghold, even though it wasn't very compelling for a lot of people, people

950
00:49:13,349 --> 00:49:17,432
did buy those upgrades, and I think those upgrades probably could have served us better

951
00:49:17,432 --> 00:49:20,253
to have those high-end upgrades be very, very expensive.

952
00:49:20,253 --> 00:49:24,235
They don't necessarily have to be proportional as long as there is something of value that

953
00:49:24,235 --> 00:49:27,938
the player can buy and they feel like, oh, okay, there's something to actually look forward

954
00:49:27,938 --> 00:49:29,158
to spending my gold on.

955
00:49:29,158 --> 00:49:30,419
But no, that was our fault.

956
00:49:30,419 --> 00:49:32,460
We designed a few sinks.

957
00:49:32,920 --> 00:49:37,945
people didn't like them. I think they're justified not liking

958
00:49:37,945 --> 00:49:40,587
them. And we didn't do a good job of fixing the economy later

959
00:49:40,587 --> 00:49:40,968
on.

960
00:49:40,968 --> 00:49:50,336
Thanks for the talk. Do you have some features that for one

961
00:49:50,336 --> 00:49:54,100
reason or another didn't make it in the final build?

962
00:49:55,312 --> 00:49:56,813
Game mechanics?

963
00:49:56,813 --> 00:49:59,595
Features or game mechanics that couldn't make it into the final build?

964
00:49:59,595 --> 00:50:01,916
What you wanted to build.

965
00:50:01,916 --> 00:50:04,177
Yeah, there were a lot of...

966
00:50:04,177 --> 00:50:08,100
We wanted to have more diverse abilities for a lot of the characters.

967
00:50:08,100 --> 00:50:09,521
People remember...

968
00:50:09,521 --> 00:50:12,702
There were a lot of really weird and wacky spells and things like that in D&D.

969
00:50:12,702 --> 00:50:13,463
And...

970
00:50:13,463 --> 00:50:17,385
I can't remember specific ones off the top of my head, but...

971
00:50:17,665 --> 00:50:19,926
If you look through the player's handbook as a developer,

972
00:50:19,926 --> 00:50:21,926
there's a lot of things in D&D where you go like,

973
00:50:21,926 --> 00:50:23,647
I don't know how I would ever implement that,

974
00:50:23,647 --> 00:50:26,027
or wow, that would be like a week of someone's time

975
00:50:26,027 --> 00:50:26,688
to implement that.

976
00:50:26,688 --> 00:50:28,808
So there are things like that that we wanted to put in

977
00:50:28,808 --> 00:50:30,488
where we're like, that's really cool,

978
00:50:30,488 --> 00:50:31,949
but it's just so expensive to put in.

979
00:50:31,949 --> 00:50:34,029
But then again, it is important to have

980
00:50:34,029 --> 00:50:35,530
at least some of that stuff.

981
00:50:35,530 --> 00:50:38,210
By the way, so Adam Brennecke, who's our lead,

982
00:50:38,210 --> 00:50:40,891
he's our executive producer and our lead programmer.

983
00:50:41,171 --> 00:50:46,813
He hates rangers so much in our game because the animal companions complicate everything

984
00:50:46,813 --> 00:50:50,895
But the design of the class is sort of built around having that companion

985
00:50:50,895 --> 00:50:56,877
And so that's like so fundamental to it that it was important that no you like we just got to fix it

986
00:50:56,877 --> 00:50:59,178
We got to keep on going. This is kind of how the class works

987
00:50:59,738 --> 00:51:01,599
We did also want to have familiars in the game

988
00:51:01,599 --> 00:51:03,660
so that wizards could have their own little dudes.

989
00:51:03,660 --> 00:51:07,822
That made Adam's mind explode because he's like, oh, cool.

990
00:51:07,822 --> 00:51:09,763
We get to have two different types of animal companions

991
00:51:09,763 --> 00:51:11,824
for twice the bugs.

992
00:51:11,824 --> 00:51:14,305
So that felt less important for wizards,

993
00:51:14,305 --> 00:51:15,566
and so we didn't incorporate that.

994
00:51:15,566 --> 00:51:15,746
Thanks.

995
00:51:15,746 --> 00:51:16,146
Any other questions?

996
00:51:16,146 --> 00:51:16,346
All right.

